<h id='clientsideXsltInMozilla'><a href="https://w3future.com/weblog/2004/12/24.xml#a282" class="weblogItemTitle">Client-side XSLT in Mozilla</a></h>
<p>The <a href="?notransform">try <acronym title="eXtensible HyperText Markup Language">XHTML</acronym> 2.0</a> link at the top now also works in Mozilla (or it works again, don't remember.) It turns out that Mozilla doesn't like it when there's a <code>document.write</code> in the output of client-side XSLT. Internet Explorer has no problem with that. I don't personally use document.write, but Nedstat and Google Adsense do.</p>
<p>Adding <code>&lt;xsl:if test="system-property('xsl:vendor')!='Transformiix'"&gt;</code> around the scripts did the trick.</p>
